	Basic - great location	This hotel is all about its location, which is perfect. There was nothing at all bad about the hotel, it is clean, the staff were good and it was quite quiet - our room was small but the bathroom was a decent size. It is basic but it never pretends to be anything else. A good place if the majority of your trip is to explore the city. All round very satisfactory.	
Nov 23 2009 	Best budget choice for SF tourists	I always advise first-time visitors to San Francisco to stay in the Union Square area. It is and always has been the heart and soul of the city, and it remains the most upscale and desirable location for out-of-towners. But I do suggest that they map any hotel they're interested in, because a number of the properties that advertise their location as &quot;Union Square&quot; are actually 5-10 blocks away. In downtown SF, even two blocks can mean the difference between upscale and ghetto. So this hotel receives high marks right off the bat for being in the very heart of Union Square, just around the corner from Macy's, and the Powell Street cable running past the front door. Although this a 100-year-old property, you wouldn't know it from the appearance of the guest rooms. The owners have recently completed a major renovation, with new paint, carpets, furniture and fixtures, eliminating every trace of the musty smell common in these old buildings, and creating a very warm relaxing environment. The rooms are small, no doubt, but perfectly adequate. The majority of travelers, especially those used to the older hotels in Europe, won't have a problem. Our suite was on the fifth floor front, facing the street and with the bedroom sharing a wall with the elevator shaft, yet the room was extremely quiet. If you have kids I recommend the family suite, with one room with two twin beds and a second bedroom in back with a queen. Both rooms have wall-mounted flat screen TV's and phones. The service at this hotel is the friendliest I've experienced in any hotel in San Francisco. The complimentary breakfast is decent cereal, toast, muffins, juice and coffee. It does the job, although some fruit, and maybe a cereal option for kids (rather than just granola) would be nice. The breakfast room is light and airy and enjoys a great view of the action on Powell Street. Overall, this has to be the best choice for budget travel in the city. The location is the main selling point, but this hotel offers clean, quiet rooms and friendly service for a very affordable rate, so I'd recommend it even if it were off the beaten path.	
