Jan 26 2008 	Good location that's all..	We arrived late in the evening from Los Angeles by long driving. We booked a standard room and a deluxe room. My aunt and her husband was not able to sleep well because it was warm &amp; stuffy in their room, being in the back and the window opens to a wall. The room is small. Our deluxe room has 2 doubles with the window facing the street. We had a good night's sleep as we were so tired from the 8 hour trip. The deluxe room on the 3rd floor, I think we were in room 303, was ok for us except that there is not much space in the bathroom for toiletries. I even gave housekeeping tip but I find it strange she did not replenished soap &amp; shampoo supply. Weird. I saw their family room on the same floor because we were supposed to transfer but it was available for just 1 night. It looks homey. A family of 4 up to 6 will be comfortable here.  The receptionist when we checked in was nice &amp; friendly. The other one the next day is not so nice &amp; accommodating.  We booked this hotel because my parents' choices, Chancellor &amp; Handlery were fully booked as early as 1st week of September. We found out that there is a scheduled Pediatrics' Convention that week. No wonder the prices were a bit high. I enjoyed all my breakfasts here. 2 kinds of coffee, 2 kinds of milk, cereal, 2 kinds of bread, 2 kinds of muffins, jams, butter. This is a charming breakfast room that overlooks Powell Street. Though my mom prefers a heavier breakfast that she goes to Chancellor for her eggs benedict. Location is superb, no question. We had lunch at a thai eatery a few doors down the street. It was full during lunch. Next door is Lush, which you can still smell on the stairways of the hotel. A few steps is Union Square. Very ideal location of the hotel. I find it enjoyable in the evenings to sit on the bed with my laptop and hearing the cable car pass by. Their hotel website which boasts of &quot;San Francisco vibe&quot; is true. However, my mom is a light sleeper but I slept well even with the San Fran street noise. In fairness, the hotel provides ear plugs. Like in all parts of San Fran, parking is expensive at $45. There is no free internet here. The flaw that we experienced here is that the phone in our room is not working. That is why a relative who was trying to call us did not get through. We had to use our Philippine cell phone to communicate with her. And this was expensive! I informed the front desk of this but they did not do anything about it and worse, when we said it to the manager when we were checking out, he just shrugged. Would I stay here again? Maybe, if I happen to be in San Fran and all my preferred hotels are fully booked and this is the last choice. Otherwise, I recommend the other C-Two property, Hotel Fusion. Stratford and Hotel Fusion are both C-Two property but they are a world apart in comparison.	
