Mar 16 2007 	Great little hotel superb location friendly staff good room	This hotel is in the most amazing location in San Francisco, a few yards from Union Square. If you don't know San Francisco, Union Square is at its heart, more so than Fisherman's Wharf, the Financial District or the Chinatown/North Beach area. Union Square is a newly remodeled square with the biggest department stores, some of the best hotels and many restaurants, bars and fast food joints around it. It really is a very bustling area, even into the night. About a two minute walk to the south of the hotel is another fantastic draw - the San Francisco Shopping Center on Market Street, which is a newly opened mall with a multiplex Cinema. Chinatown is about a ten-minute walk away to the north. Fisherman’s Wharf is about two miles away and is an easy half hour walk through Chinatown. The city’s main Disney, Apple and Virgin stores are all within a minute or two of the hotel.From the hotel you can get to almost anywhere in the city with ease. You have direct access to the cable cars, which run outside the hotel for about 18 hours a day and take you to Nob Hill, Chinatown, North Beach, Fisherman’s Wharf, Aquatic Park and Russian Hill. Also within a couple of minutes walk is the Muni Subway (the city’s tram system that runs underground for part of the city) as well as the BART rapid transport system, which takes you direct to the airport for a $5.15 half hour trip. Of course the area is also served by the regular bus service and the open-top double decker tourist buses have a stop a 30 second walk away outside Macy’s department store.The hotel itself is a bargain for the price; I paid $69 for a fairly good-sized room (nowhere near as cramped as some reviewers state) with a newly refurbished bathroom. I had a built in closet and a writing desk with drawers. The only downside to the room I had at the back of the hotel was no view and I mean no view, unless you count a brick wall about three feet away from the window a view! The brick wall seems to be about 100 feet high and I think it is the back of Macy’s department store. However, generally this isolates you from the noise of Union Square (people sometimes play electric guitars connected to amps in the evening near the hotel!!) and you can get a nice quiet night’s sleep. One thing though, I stayed at the hotel for six nights, and the noise from other guests on the Friday and Saturday was quite loud i.e. some of them were drunk and were occasionally loud about it (slamming doors, loud talking/laughing in the early hours). If you have the window open, the wall outside the window tends bounce the sound into your room from the other guests if they too have their window open. However, from Monday through Thursday it was peace and quiet even with the window open all night. On Friday and Saturday I wore some earplugs though and that did the trick. The noise from other guests wasn’t really a problem and nowhere near as bad as the loud traffic or nocturnal street noise (i.e. shouting and fights) that you would no doubt experience from the street facing rooms. The hotel is in the entertainment district of the city after all and there are lots of bars about.The breakfast served by the hotel was very good bearing in mind the cost of the room, and consisted of three different types of muffins plus toast, yogurt with optional dried fruit, granola (oat crunch for us Europeans), tea, coffee and fruit juices. The breakfast room overlooked Powell Street and was spacious with plenty of tables. Free copies of the San Francisco Chronicle were available in the breakfast room.The hotel will expect pre-payment of at least one night's stay upon arrival. There is an Internet area in the small lounge behind reception; this was about $5.00 for 30 minutes. The service used new equipment on a broadband connection. There is a swipe-card reader for a credit card built into the PC to activate the connection. Some people complain about the smell of cleaning fluid in their room, I think they are mistaken. There is a ‘Lush’ hand made soap store next to the hotel, which makes its products on the premises, the rather nice small from this place seems to permeate some of the hotel. The hotel is happy to store luggage for you, which they did for me when I checked out, as I wanted to spend some time in the city before my flight. Apparently they can offer an airport shuttle but as there is a BART station offering a direct fast service to the International terminal at San Francisco Airport about two minutes walk away I don't think the airport shuttle is necessary.The staff at he hotel were all very friendly, especially the check in staff. For the price, this hotel is an absolute bargain. The rooms are a good size and they look recently refurbished, you have a decent new bathroom (no bath, a nice hot powerful shower though), a good breakfast, friendly staff and a location to die for. This isn't a hotel that you will lounge around in, but when you are visiting a city why would you want to spend any time at the hotel? If you want to lounge about go to any of the swanky lobby bars of the nearby four or five star hotels. I suggest the Polynesian Tonga room at the Fairmont hotel on Nob Hill, it is an absolute hoot, especially when the fake thunderstorm gets going!	
Mar 9 2007 	Great inexpensive hotel in heart of SF	We were very happy with our stay here. The rooms are VERY small, we didn't have a view (except of a brick wall), but we stayed in the center of SF for less than $70 a night, and that's hard to beat. This hotel is more in the European style - the room is not where you will be spending most of your time, so why bother making it huge?Everything was clean enough that we were comfortable. The free breakfast was good enough to get your day started, and the staff was helpful all the time, and friendly most of the time. We have already recommended this hotel to several of our friends and acquaintances and will return when we next go to SF.	
